Finger,     Thank you so much for your time and all the information! I looked up the http://www.taifex.com.tw/ as your suggested and kinda browsed thru the 30 plus options and they are indeed traded very lightly, it's like there is little or no market existed for these options, liquidity is a major issue.    How are firms handling their risk?  With little or no futures/options market, there is very limit thing you can do in terms of risk management, right?  Well, I guess one could always hedge against these indexes futures/options contract but that's basically it.Deviated from the subject for a moment, Finger, also let me run this by you and please let me your suggestions/opinions on this:I have dealt with Goldman Sach's core valuation system, SecDB, for many years now and I have also built a valuation system myself for my other client with a more modernized technology to do IRFX calculation, MTM valuation in the energy commodity world such as power, nature gas, coal, and cruel.  It can do futures/options and other derivative such as the new weather derivative just launched by NYMEX.  The system will show traderâ€™s current market position to help determine if the trader has exceeded his/her VaR limit and all the Greeks the trader needs to help him/her build the hedging strategies.  And this is what I want to do and I am sure someone may already have done it, but I want to built it into my product as value added, I want to extend the system to be able to provide trader hedging strategies on the fly based on the market condition at the time such as suggesting options fences, delta adjust or swap trade suggestion with commodity that has highest correlation coefficient or even speculative trading strategies such as straddles and strangles if one is certain which way the market is going to go.  Portfolio manager then can view these strategies near real-time and make decision on the spot!       Once I have the system built and complete, I wish to use it on the stock market and theoretically speaking it shouldnâ€™t be a problem, if not easier!  Personally, I think the main benefits of such system are: speed, accuracy, and control (especially for SOX control).  It certainly will change the business process from front office to back office but itâ€™s all for good, less work for RMG people to reduce tension between risk manager and traders if you know what I mean  ï¿½ï¿½ In your opinion, do you think such system can provide value to finacial firms in Taiwan?  Does such system exist in Taiwan (and no, I don't mean excel )  If not for anything else, would it be a good educational tool for people to use to educate themself on options by providing people an online options trading simulator and help them understand the risk associated with it?  Kindly advice.See, this thread may just initiate a whole new idea for my http://cash.com.tw...  to build an online trading simulator with stock/future/options trading educational material, trade simulator, VaR/MTM calculator and finally, how about this: your own virtual risk manager that will always listen to you, do as your say and not fight with you!!!   For everyone else reading this thread, advice are welcomed!


    	    	
